<span id="iii.ix.xi"></span>

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="iii.ix.xi-p1.1"></span>Chapter XI.—</span>*The Heresiarchs of that
Age*.

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p2"></span>1. “<span class="c13"><span
id="iii.ix.xi-p2.1"></span>For</span> Valentinus came to Rome under
Hyginus, flourished under Pius, and remained until Anicetus. <span
id="fr_1064"></span>[1065](#fn_1064.md) Cerdon <span
id="fr_1065"></span>[1066](#fn_1065.md) also, Mar<span id="page_183">p.
183</span> <span id="iii.ix.xi-Page_183"></span>cion’s <span
id="fr_1066"></span>[1067](#fn_1066.md) predecessor, entered the Church in
the time of Hyginus, the ninth <span
id="fr_1067"></span>[1068](#fn_1067.md) bishop, and made confession, and
continued in this way, now teaching in secret, now making confession
again, and now denounced for corrupt doctrine and withdrawing <span
id="fr_1068"></span>[1069](#fn_1068.md) from the assembly of the brethren.”

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p8"></span>2. These words are found in the third
book of the work Against Heresies. And again in the first book he speaks
as follows concerning Cerdon: <span id="fr_1069"></span>[1070](#fn_1069.md)
“A certain Cerdon, who had taken his system from the followers of Simon,
and had come to Rome under Hyginus, the ninth in the episcopal
succession from the apostles, <span id="fr_1070"></span>[1071](#fn_1070.md)
taught that the God proclaimed by the law and prophets was not the
father of our Lord Jesus Christ. For the former was known, but the
latter unknown; and the former was just, but the latter good. <span
id="fr_1071"></span>[1072](#fn_1071.md) Marcion of Pontus succeeded Cerdon
and developed his doctrine, uttering shameless blasphemies.”

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p12"></span>3. The same Irenæus unfolds with the
greatest vigor the unfathomable abyss of Valentinus’ errors in regard to
matter, and reveals his wickedness, secret and hidden like a serpent
lurking in its nest.

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p13"></span>4. And in addition to these men he says
that there was also another that lived in that age, Marcus by
name, <span id="fr_1072"></span>[1073](#fn_1072.md) who was remarkably
skilled in magic arts. And he describes also their unholy initiations
and their abominable mysteries in the following words: <span
id="fr_1073"></span>[1074](#fn_1073.md)

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p16"></span>5. “For some of them prepare a nuptial
couch and perform a mystic rite with certain forms of expression
addressed to those who are being initiated, and they say that it is a
spiritual marriage which is celebrated by them, after the likeness of
the marriages above. But others lead them to water, and while they
baptize them they repeat the following words: Into the name of the
unknown father of the universe, into truth, the mother of all things,
into the one that descended upon Jesus. <span
id="fr_1074"></span>[1075](#fn_1074.md) Others repeat Hebrew names <span
id="fr_1075"></span>[1076](#fn_1075.md) in order the better to confound
those who are being initiated.”

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p19"></span>6. But Hyginus <span
id="fr_1076"></span>[1077](#fn_1076.md) having died at the close of the
fourth year of his episcopate, Pius <span
id="fr_1077"></span>[1078](#fn_1077.md) <span id="page_184">p. 184</span>
<span id="iii.ix.xi-Page_184"></span>succeeded him in the government of
the church of Rome. In Alexandria Marcus <span
id="fr_1078"></span>[1079](#fn_1078.md) was appointed pastor, after
Eumenes <span id="fr_1079"></span>[1080](#fn_1079.md) had filled the office
thirteen years in all. And Marcus having died after holding office ten
years was succeeded by Celadion <span
id="fr_1080"></span>[1081](#fn_1080.md) in the government of the church of
Alexandria.

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p25"></span>7. And in Rome Pius died in the
fifteenth year of his episcopate, and Anicetus <span
id="fr_1081"></span>[1082](#fn_1081.md) assumed the leadership of the
Christians there. Hegesippus records that he himself was in Rome at this
time, and that he remained there until the episcopate of
Eleutherus. <span id="fr_1082"></span>[1083](#fn_1082.md)

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p28"></span>8. But Justin <span
id="fr_1083"></span>[1084](#fn_1083.md) was especially prominent in those
days. In the guise of a philosopher <span
id="fr_1084"></span>[1085](#fn_1084.md) he preached the divine word, and
contended for the faith in his writings. He wrote also a work against
Marcion, <span id="fr_1085"></span>[1086](#fn_1085.md) in which he states
that the latter was alive at the time he wrote.

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p33"></span>9. He speaks as follows: <span
id="fr_1086"></span>[1087](#fn_1086.md) “And there is a certain
Marcion <span id="fr_1087"></span>[1088](#fn_1087.md) of Pontus, <span
id="fr_1088"></span>[1089](#fn_1088.md) who is even now <span
id="page_185">p. 185</span> <span id="iii.ix.xi-Page_185"></span>still
teaching his followers to think that there is some other God greater
than the creator. And by the aid of the demons <span
id="fr_1089"></span>[1090](#fn_1089.md) he has persuaded many of every race
of men <span id="fr_1090"></span>[1091](#fn_1090.md) to utter blasphemy,
and to deny that the maker of this universe is the father of Christ, and
to confess that some other, greater than he, was the creator. <span
id="fr_1091"></span>[1092](#fn_1091.md) And all who followed them are, as
we have said, <span id="fr_1092"></span>[1093](#fn_1092.md) called
Christians, just as the name of philosophy is given to philosophers,
although they may have no doctrines in common.”

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p42"></span>10. To this he adds: <span
id="fr_1093"></span>[1094](#fn_1093.md) “And we have also written a work
against all the heresies that have existed, <span
id="fr_1094"></span>[1095](#fn_1094.md) which we will give you if you wish
to read it.”

<span id="iii.ix.xi-p45"></span>11. But this same Justin contended most
successfully against the Greeks, and addressed discourses containing an
apology for our faith to the Emperor Antoninus, called Pius, and to the
Roman senate. <span id="fr_1095"></span>[1096](#fn_1095.md) For he lived at
Rome. But who and whence he was he shows in his Apology in the following
words. <span id="fr_1096"></span>[1097](#fn_1096.md)

